\f0\b \cf2 \cb5 Workflow
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl600\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf2 \cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Create a new directory and name it \'93liveProject.\'94 This location is the working directory, and is where we will develop our project.\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Within the directory, create a second directory and name it \'93jupyter.\'94 Then, in the jupyter directory, create a\'a0
\f0\b Dockerfile
\f1\b0 . This Dockerfile represents the image we will use to run Jupyter.\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 In the Dockerfile, define as base a Python image. A smaller one like\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://hub.docker.com/_/python"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2 \cf6 \strokec6 python:3.7-slim}}\'a0should suffice. Then, use the\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 RUN
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0instruction with command\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 mkdir src
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0to create a\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 /src
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0directory inside the container. Use the\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 WORKDIR
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0instruction to set\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 /src
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0as the working directory.\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 In the Dockerfile, add another\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 RUN
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0that installs Jupyter using\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/"}}{\fldrslt 
\f2 \cf6 \strokec6 pip}}, which is the Python package installer.\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Next, use the\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 CMD
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0instruction to specify the command that starts the Jupyter server.\
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sl600\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl1\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Since we are inside a Docker container and we want to access Jupyter from the outside, we need to use the following options while starting the Jupyter server:\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 no-browser
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0and\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 allow-root
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 . Besides this, I\'92d recommend using the\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 ip
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0and\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 port
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0options to explicitly define the IP and port where the server will run. You could use the IP address\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 0.0.0.0
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 .\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl600\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf2 \cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	6.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 After defining the Dockerfile, on the terminal, use Docker\'92s\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 build
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0command to build the image using as name\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 \{your_name\}/lp-jupyter
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 ; for example,\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 juan/lp-jupyter
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 .\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	7.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Run the Docker image using the publish or expose option (
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 -p
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 ) to port forward the port you used in the second\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 CMD
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 \'a0command to the local machine. The command that runs the Docker image is named\'a0
\f3\fs37\fsmilli18900 \cf7 \cb8 \strokec7 run
\f1\fs42 \cf2 \cb5 \strokec2 . This command will run the Docker image and start the Jupyter server. After running it, you will see on-screen the address where Jupyter is running. Click on it to access it.\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	8.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 From Jupyter, create a new notebook and print a \'93hello, world.\'94\cb1 \
